    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Savings Rate Explained: The Most Important Number in FIRE",
    "description": "Why your savings rate matters more than your income, how to calculate gross vs. net savings rate, and the math of early retirement.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "Fire Maths"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a good savings rate for FIRE?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The traditional advice of saving 10% to 15% is meant for people retiring at 65. If you want to retire in your 30s or 40s, you typically need a savings rate between 50% and 70%."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I include employer match in my savings rate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes! If your employer matches your 401(k) contributions, that is free money going toward your net worth. Add the employer match to both your total savings and your total income when calculating your rate."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I calculate savings rate based on gross or net income?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The FIRE community generally prefers calculating savings rate based on after-tax (net) income. Taxes are a mandatory expense, so basing your math on take-home pay gives you a much clearer picture of your actual lifestyle cost and saving power."
        }
